CitiBike Report

About Citi Bike

Citi Bike is a privately owned public bicycle sharing system serving the New York City,Brooklyn, Manhattan, Queens, Jersey City, New Jersey, and Hoboken, New Jersey. Named after lead sponsor Citigroup.

Data collection detail in the next doocument submitted

Data visualisation as a tool for decision-making

This report helps to identify the patterns of bike usage in different 
groups and types of customers. It prvides insights and suggestions of 
how citi bike can imcrease their bike hiring.

Data types

There are different types of data in this data set.
Numerical, POSIXct(Datetime) and Factors

Data quality and data bias

The data set is clean.
This data only recoreded 10 bikes. 
Data was collected with no personal identifible information

1. Loading data and tidying up

library(tsibbledata)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(tsibble)
library(leaflet)
Registered S3 method overwritten by 'htmlwidgets':
  method           from         
  print.htmlwidget tools:rstudio
nyc_bikes_df <- nyc_bikes
nyc_bikes_short <- nyc_bikes_df %>% 
  select(start_time, stop_time, birth_year, gender, type) %>% 
  mutate(year = year(start_time),
         month = month(start_time, label = TRUE),
         day = as.Date(start_time),
         wday  = wday(start_time,label = TRUE),
         week = week(start_time),
         time_ride = stop_time - start_time,
         age = as.numeric(year - birth_year))

bike_90 <-nyc_bikes_short%>%
  index_by(year) %>%
  summarise(p90 = quantile(time_ride, probs=0.9, na.rm=TRUE))

nyc_bikes_short_90 <- nyc_bikes_short %>% 
  mutate(time_ride = as.numeric(time_ride)) %>% 
  filter(time_ride < bike_90$p90)
#nyc_bikes_short doesn't have locations data 
#nyc_bikes_short_90 has 90% of nyc_bikes_short based on riding time

2 Overall pattern of the year

2.1 Daily distribution over 2018

day_nyc <- nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
  group_by(day) %>% 
  count()

day_nyc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(day, n))+
  geom_line()+
  labs(x = "Days in 2018",
       y = "Number of Bike Hire",
       title = "Bike hire for each day in 2018\n")

From the grapg above, it suggestes that from Jan to Jul bike hiring increasing and the number of hiring each day starts to drop from summer to winter months.

2.2 Monthly pattern over 2018

month_nyc <- nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  count()

month_nyc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(month, n))+
  geom_line(group = 1, size = 1, col = "lightblue")+
  geom_point(col = "steelblue")+
  labs(
    x="\nMonth",
    y = "Number of Bike Hire",
    title = "Number of bike hire for each month",
    subtitle = "Data from 2018 citibike NYC\n"
  )

From the monthly disribution, we can notice that the pattern of bike hiring is very similar to the daily graph and suggests summer is the peak of the year for bike hiring.

2.3 weekly patterns

wday_nyc <- nyc_bikes_short_90%>% 
  group_by(wday) %>% 
  count()



wday_nyc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(wday, n))+
  geom_point(size = 2, col = "steelblue")+
  geom_line(group = 1, alpha = 0.7, col = "steelblue")+
   labs(
    x="Weekdays",
    y = "Number of Bike Hire",
    title = "Number of bike hire for each day of week",
    subtitle = "Data from 2018 citibike NYC\n"
  )

Across the whole year of 2018, the graph suggests that the numbers of bike hiring is higher during the weekdays and it lower for weekends. It could be that the most common usage are for commuting.

3. Compare between genders, ages and types.

3.1 Gender overall and over the year

nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(gender, n))+
  geom_col(aes(fill = gender, col = gender))+
  labs(x = "Gender",
       y = "Number of bikr hire",
       title = "Gender bike hire in 2018")

This graph shows an overview of bike hiring for each gender in 2018. Male users are a lot higher than the other two groups.

gender_m <- nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  index_by(month) %>% 
  count()

gender_m %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = n))+
  geom_line(aes(col = gender), group = 1)+
  geom_point(aes(col = gender), size = 2)+
  facet_wrap(~gender,ncol =1)+
  labs(x = "Month",
       y = "Number of bike hire",
       title = "Bike hire pattern for each gender")

The hiring pattern seems to be similar as we descoved before. All groups have a peak around summer months and male hiring are a lot higher than the other two groups.

3.2 Age overall and over weekdays

I used age groups are as following: 18-30, 30-60, 60 and above. I am interested in mostly over 60 group as I think they will show different pattern over a week as youger groups.

nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
   mutate( age_group = case_when(age < 18 ~ "Under 18",
                        age < 30 ~"18 to 30",
                        age < 60 ~"30 to 60",
                        TRUE ~"60 and above")) %>% 
  group_by(age_group) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(age_group, n))+
  geom_col(aes(fill = age_group, col = age_group))+
  labs(x = "Age Group",
       y = "Number of bikr hire",
       fill = "Age Group",
       col = "Age Group",
       title = "Bike hiring for each age group")

The overall graph shows that most of the bike hiring are from 30-60 age group. However, it is the biggest age group. It is not very fair to use this grouping.

nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
   mutate( age_group = case_when(age < 18 ~ "Under 18",
                        age < 30 ~"18 to 30",
                        age < 60 ~"30 to 60",
                        TRUE ~"60 and above")) %>% 
  group_by(age_group) %>% 
  index_by(wday) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(wday, n))+
  geom_point(size = 2, aes(col = age_group))+
  geom_line(group = 1, alpha = 0.7, aes(col = age_group))+
  facet_wrap(~age_group, ncol = 1,scales = "free_y")+
   labs(
    x="Weekdays",
    y = "Number of Bike Hire",
    col = "Age Group",
    fill = "Age Group",
    title = "Bike hiring for each age group of weekdays"
  )

Supprisingly, for all the groups it shows similar pattern as the whole data group(bike hiring are mostly in weekdays), Even for over 60 groups which higher percentage of them among general population don’t need to commute for work.

3.3 Types of customers, overall and over the year

nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
  group_by(type) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(type, n))+
  geom_col(aes(fill = type, col = type))+
  labs(x = "Type of costomers",
       y = "Number of bikr hire",
       col = "Costomer types",
       fill = "Costomer types",
       title = "Bike hire for differnt costomer types")

Most the customers are subscribers and only small percentages are not.

type_d <- nyc_bikes_short_90 %>% 
  group_by(type) %>% 
  index_by(day) %>% 
  count()

type_d %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = day, y = n))+
  geom_line(aes(col = type))+
  facet_wrap(~type,ncol =1, scales = "free_y")+
  labs(x = "Day",
       y = "Number of bike hire",
       col = "Type",
       title = "Bike Hire Pattern for Different Types of Hiring")

This graph shows the patterns of bike hiring of differnt types over 2018. for subscribers, they have very similar pattern as the overall data group. High peaks in summer and lower number of hiring in winter. However for “Cusomer” type, the pattern shows sharp increasing and sharp drop throughout the year and it also has time period that no “customer” are hiring in a day. This is due to the fact that not many users are this type and it not expected to see a steaby amount everyday.

4. Locations

nyc_bikes_df %>% 
  group_by(start_long, start_lat) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  head(5) %>% 
leaflet() %>% 
  addTiles() %>% 
  addMarkers(
    lng = ~start_long,
    lat = ~start_lat,
    clusterOptions = markerClusterOptions()
  )

The spacial graph above shows the top 5 most popular stations, all of they are very close to big public transport stations and most of them are located in downtown.

nyc_bikes_df %>% 
  filter(type == "Customer") %>% 
leaflet() %>% 
  addTiles() %>% 
  addMarkers(
    lng = ~start_long,
    lat = ~start_lat,
    clusterOptions = markerClusterOptions()
  )

Assume that all the customer types are visitors, they should use the top 5 stations to travel into the city. From the graph above they do seems to use the major stations more but there are small other stations been used.

5 Data ethics

Data used is open data from CitiBike and collected with consent

Analysis only looks at trends rather than one spcific data

This set had a sample of 10 bike so it’s not very representative for whole population

6 Conclusion and recommendations

The KPI is to increase bike hiring, we noticed the difference in male and female customers, the company should encourage female customers. Marketing among female population. Encourage visitors to hire citibike, we can have more bikes around big public stations.
